training_organizations.name: New Jersey DCF Child Welfare Training Academy (Rutgers)
training_organizations.description: A training academy developed through Rutgers University’s Institute for Families in partnership with the NJ Department of Children & Families. It trains all incoming child welfare staff (including investigators and caseworkers) on New Jersey’s practice model (Strengthening Families), case planning, and court processes. It also provides specialized training to community providers and resource families, standardizing knowledge across the child welfare system.

training_organizations.name: Children’s Home Society of New Jersey
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit that provides extensive services under contract with New Jersey’s DCF. CHS of NJ handles foster home recruitment and licensing, adoption promotion and support services, and early childhood programs. As part of New Jersey’s network of private providers, it works to find foster and adoptive families for children and to offer in-home programs that prevent placement or expedite reunification:contentReference[oaicite:30]{index=30}.

training_organizations.name: CarePlus New Jersey
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit organization that DCF contracts for in-home counseling and intervention services. CarePlus NJ provides behavioral health services, peer recovery (for substance-affected families), and other intensive in-home supports for families involved with CPS. These services help address issues like mental health or substance use within families, so children can remain safely at home or return home sooner:contentReference[oaicite:31]{index=31}.

training_organizations.name: Evident Change (Structured Decision Making)
training_organizations.description: New Jersey’s DCF has implemented Evident Change’s Structured Decision Making assessment tools statewide:contentReference[oaicite:32]{index=32}. This partnership provides NJ with research-based risk and safety assessment forms and training for staff, which guide caseworkers in making consistent removal, service, and reunification decisions based on objective criteria.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.ReportAnonymous: General public (not mandated reporters) can remain anonymous
policies.Def_OtherSpecify: Continued inappropriate placement of a child in an institution with the knowledge that the placement has resulted and may continue to result in harm to the child's mental or physical well-being
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes failure to provide proper and sufficient food, clothing, education, or medical attendance or surgical treatment, a clean and proper home, and continued placement of a child in an institution with the knowledge that the placement has harmed the child's well-being
policies.EquityStaff_Specify: The state Office of Diversity, Equity, and Belonging supports efforts to become an antiracist system by addressing racial bias, disproportionality, disparities, and inequities; address diversity and inclusion issues involving African Americans, people of color, women, gender and sexual orientation; and create a culture of belonging for all people within our organization that respects and embraces difference and treats everyone equitably. A Race Equity Steering Committee studies the state's data and policies, researches best practices, and engages experts in the field. The Steering Committee provides regular updates to the department, and shares resources and information that promote race equity. The state has outside consultants that have trained all staff (including casework staff) to ensure cultural competence and race equity in all aspects of their work.
policies.Exempt_OtherSpecify: Homelessness due to lack of community housing resources is exempt for inadequate shelter
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.InvestReq_OtherSpecify: Assess the strengths and needs of the caregiver; Assess the strengths and needs of the alleged child victim; Confirm child care arrangements reported by the caregiver where appropriate; Interview each witness offered by the alleged perpetrator who could provide evidence that he or she did not abuse or neglect the alleged child victim; Interview each investigative law enforcement officer working on the report; Interview each of the primary response law enforcement personnel called to the scene of the alleged abuse or neglect; Obtain, if possible, a certified copy of any medical report
policies.InvestQual_OtherSpecify: Driver's license, if the operation of a vehicle is necessary to perform essential duties of the position
policies.ReportInfo_OtherSpecify: Any other information that the person believes may be helpful with respect to the child abuse and the identity of the perpetrator
policies.EquityStaff_OtherSpecify: The Race Equity Steering Committee reviews the department's policies and practices to identify areas in which implicit bias and racism may be impacting their work.; The Office of Diversity, Equity, and Belonging provides leadership on policies and best practices related to diversity, equity, and belonging; develops processes and procedures that scale and measure the impact of DEB; develops and implements initiatives that promote equitable outcomes for children and families of color; and builds the capacity of staff at all levels to respond effectively to structural racism and individual and implicit bias
policies.InvestStaff_OtherSpecify: County or state medical examiners; County prosecutor's office
policies.ScreenerQual_OtherSpecify: Driver's license, if the operation of a vehicle is necessary to perform essential duties of the position
policies.CaseManagerQual_OtherSpecify: Driver's license, if the operation of a vehicle is necessary to perform essential duties of the position
policies.InvestQual_ExperienceSpecify: 5 years of professional experience in social work, direct support counseling, guidance, or case management involving high risk child abuse and neglect or other problematic situations; 4 years of professional experience and 300 hours of supervised social work field placement; 1 year of professional experience or 300 hours of supervised social work field placement with a bachelor's degree; No experience required for a master's degree
policies.CaseManagerQual_ExperienceSpec: 5 years of professional experience in social work, direct support counseling, guidance, or case management involving high risk child abuse and neglect or other problematic situations; 4 years of professional experience and 300 hours of supervised social work field placement; 1 year of professional experience or 300 hours of supervised social work field placement with a bachelor's degree; No experience required for a master's degree
policies.NearFatalities_SpecificSpecify: A serious or vital condition, resulting in the child receiving critical care for at least 24 hours following the child's admission to a critical care unit, and the child suffered at least one of the following, as documented by a physician: severe permanent mental or physical impairment; a life-threatening injury; or a condition that creates a probability of death within the near future
policies.ScreenerQual_ExperienceSpecify: 5 years of professional experience in social work, direct support counseling, guidance, or case management involving high risk child abuse and neglect or other problematic situations; 4 years of professional experience and 300 hours of supervised social work field placement; 1 year of professional experience or 300 hours of supervised social work field placement with a bachelor's degree; No experience required for a master's degree
policies.ExtFosterCare_Reentry_OtherSpec: Youth must have been receiving services on or after their 16th birthday
policies.ExtFosterCare_Criteria_OtherSpec: Youth must be between 18 and 21 years of age and meet the following conditions: (a) The individual was receiving services from the department, on or after the individual's 16th birthday; (b) The individual, on or after the individual's 18th birthday, has not refused or requested that these services be terminated, as applicable; and (c) The commissioner determines that a continuation of services would be in the individual's best interest and would assist the individual to become an independent and productive adult
